Project Goals

While initially Id planned to look at economic growth somewhat widely, Ive chosen to specify the goal of my project to better understand the dynamics of economic growth and inequality throughout the course of history, hopefully allowing me to make some predictions and theorize on the potential impact of future policy decisions.

Collaboration Plan

As a graduate student I will be working alone, but plan on leveraging all resources made available to me both on campus and off to ensure that I am staying on track, getting the advice and assistance I need, and achieving the goal of this project.

Project Dataset

I will be using three datasets, the Penn World Tables 11.0 dataset found here, the Maddison Project Database update from 2020 found here, and the World Inequality database found here, most recently updated in 2023. The Penn World Tables (PWT) data provides information on relative levels of income, output, input and productivity, covering 185 countries between 1950 and 2023. The Maddison Project data provides historical estimates of real GDP and population for countries extending back as far as the year 1 CE, allowing me to gain an expanded view into economic development historically. Its consistent cross-country methodology makes it possible to compare growth trajectories across major economies and identify structural transitions such as industrialization, postwar recovery, and long-run convergence or divergence. Crucially it supplies the essential long-run GDP per capita series needed to analyze how growth patterns evolve alongside changes in inequality. Lastly, I will be adding in the World Inequality Databases (WID) most recent update from 2023. The WID data provides detailed, internationally comparable measures of income and wealth distribution, built from tax records, national accounts, and household surveys. It offers a variety of inequality indicatorsincluding top income shares and bottom-50% shares that allow meaningful comparisons across countries and over time. This dataset will provide the essential inequality series needed to study how shifts in income distribution relate to long-run economic growth.

ETL (Extraction, Transform, and Load)

I have loaded all 3 of my datasets. First, I extracted the raw inequality data from the World Inequality Database, keeping only the variables that represent true income shares. I then transformed the data by mapping percentile codes to more meaningful labels, reshaping it into a countryyear table, converting fractions to percentages, and creating additional variables for the Top 10% Share, Top 101% share, Bottom 50% share, and Top 1% share. Next, I loaded the Maddison Project and Penn World Table datasets, cleaned their year and GDP variables, and computed long-run growth measures like log growth and 10-year rolling average growth. Finally, I merged all three cleaned datasetsWID, MPD, and PWTinto a single file organized by country and year. The result is a fully cleaned and merged dataset that combines long-run growth, modern macroeconomic indicators, and inequality measures, and should enable me to gain insight into some of the trends I will begin to unpack below.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import os

# Load WID file to clean inequality variables
wid = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/CMPS Project Data/df_WID_merged.csv")

# Keep only the relevant WID variable
wid_shares = wid[wid["variable"] == "sptincj999"].copy()

# Map percentiles to actual income-share concepts
perc_map = {
    "p99p100": "top1_share",
    "p90p100": "top10_share",
    "p0p50":   "bottom50_share"
}

wid_shares = wid_shares[wid_shares["percentile"].isin(perc_map.keys())]
wid_shares["series"] = wid_shares["percentile"].map(perc_map)

# Pivot
wid_clean = wid_shares.pivot_table(
    index=["country", "year"],
    columns="series",
    values="value"
).reset_index()

# Convert fractions to percentages
for col in ["top1_share", "top10_share", "bottom50_share"]:
    wid_clean[col] = wid_clean[col] * 100

# Create top 101% share
wid_clean["top10_1_share"] = wid_clean["top10_share"] - wid_clean["top1_share"]

# Sort and save
wid_clean = wid_clean.sort_values(["country", "year"])
wid_clean.to_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/CMPS Project Data/wid_clean_inequality.csv", index=False)

print(wid_clean.head())
print(wid_clean.describe())

# Load datasets to merge
mpd = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/CMPS Project Data/mpd2020.csv")
pwt = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/CMPS Project Data/pwt110.csv")
wid = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/CMPS Project Data/wid_clean_inequality.csv")

# Keep only core countries
countries = ["United States", "United Kingdom", "France", "Germany", "Japan"]

mpd = mpd[mpd["country"].isin(countries)].copy()
pwt = pwt[pwt["country"].isin(countries)].copy()
wid = wid[wid["country"].isin(countries)].copy()

# Clean MPD (Maddison) and compute growth terms
mpd["year"] = pd.to_numeric(mpd["year"], errors="coerce")

# Clean gdppc (remove commas, convert to float)
mpd["gdppc"] = (
    mpd["gdppc"]
    .astype(str)
    .str.replace(",", "", regex=False)
)

mpd["gdppc"] = pd.to_numeric(mpd["gdppc"], errors="coerce")

# Compute log GDP per capita growth (year-over-year, %)
mpd["g_gdppc"] = (
    mpd.groupby("country")["gdppc"]
       .transform(lambda x: 100 * np.log(x).diff())
)

# Compute 10-year rolling growth
mpd["g10"] = (
    mpd.groupby("country")["g_gdppc"]
       .transform(lambda x: x.rolling(10, min_periods=1).mean())
)

# Clean PWT
pwt["year"] = pd.to_numeric(pwt["year"], errors="coerce")

# Clean WID inequality data
wid["year"] = pd.to_numeric(wid["year"], errors="coerce")

# Merge: MPD + WID
combined = mpd.merge(
    wid,
    on=["country", "year"],
    how="left"
)

# Merge: + PWT
combined = combined.merge(
    pwt,
    on=["country", "year"],
    how="left",
    suffixes=("", "_pwt")
)

# Save cleaned merged dataset
output_dir = "/content/drive/MyDrive/CMPS Project Data/data_clean"
os.makedirs(output_dir, exist_ok=True)

output_path = os.path.join(output_dir, "combined_data.csv")
combined.to_csv(output_path, index=False)

print("\n-----------------------------------------")
print(" CLEAN MERGE COMPLETE ")
print("-----------------------------------------")
print("Saved to:", output_path)
print("Shape:", combined.shape)
print("\nColumns:")
print(combined.columns.tolist())

Trends in Income Share by Percentile

I am going to start by filtering my data to only include a few priority countries, the US, UK, France, Germany, and Japan. There are a few reasons for this, mainly that these countries have more reliable and extensive figures, and also because these countries represent a sample of highly connected economies. While arguments could be made that there are other countries that could be included, in my research I feel that these will provide valuable insights. As a note on the data, France and the US have excellent historical data going back to the beginning of the 20th Century due largely to an interrupted chain of government and tax records, while the data for the UK, Japan, and Germany, specifically the inequality microdata, is frequently either unavailable or unreliable prior to roughly 1980 due to a number of factors, mostly poor surveying and war-related losses in archives. With these countries selected, I am going to begin to visualize the trends in income shares among the different percentiles (Top 1%, Top 10%, Top 1-10%, Bottom 50%). I am choosing to leave all 5 countries in because I think their related trends are worth seeing post 1980, but as will be seen in the plots France and US will provide the most valuable insight given that their tax records stretch back about 70 years further.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")

df = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/CMPS Project Data/data_clean/combined_data.csv")

countries = ["United States", "United Kingdom", "France", "Germany", "Japan"]
df = df[df["country"].isin(countries)].copy()

df["year"] = pd.to_numeric(df["year"], errors="coerce")
df = df[df["year"] >= 1900].copy()

for col in ["top1_share", "top10_share", "bottom50_share", "top10_1_share"]:
    if col in df.columns:
        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors="coerce")

def ts_plot(col, title, ylabel):
    if col not in df.columns:
        print(f"Column '{col}' not found  skipping.")
        return
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    for c in countries:
        temp = df[df["country"] == c]
        plt.plot(temp["year"], temp[col], label=c)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel("Year")
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.legend()
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

ts_plot("top1_share", "Top 1% Income Share Over Time", "Share of national income (%)")
ts_plot("top10_share", "Top 10% Income Share Over Time", "Share of national income (%)")
ts_plot("bottom50_share", "Bottom 50% Income Share Over Time", "Share of national income (%)")
ts_plot("top10_1_share", "Top 101% Income Share (9099th percentile)", "Share of national income (%)")

df = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/CMPS Project Data/data_clean/combined_data.csv")

df = df[df["country"].isin(countries)].copy()

# Ensure numeric
df["year"] = pd.to_numeric(df["year"], errors="coerce")
df["gdppc"] = pd.to_numeric(df["gdppc"], errors="coerce")
df["g10"] = pd.to_numeric(df["g10"], errors="coerce")

# Restrict to 1820-2020, data less reliable outside of that window.
df = df[(df["year"] >= 1820) & (df["year"] <= 2020)]

# Ensure positive GDP for log
df = df[df["gdppc"] > 0]

df = df.sort_values(["country", "year"])

# Log GDP per Capita (18202020)

    plt.plot(temp["year"], np.log(temp["gdppc"]), label=c)

plt.title("Log GDP per Capita, 18202020")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("ln(GDP per capita)")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

for c in countries:
    temp = df[df["country"] == c]
    plt.plot(temp["year"], temp["g10"], label=c)

sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")
df = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/CMPS Project Data/data_clean/combined_data.csv")
countries = ["United States", "United Kingdom", "France", "Germany", "Japan"]

df = df[df["country"].isin(countries)].copy()

df["year"] = pd.to_numeric(df["year"], errors="coerce")
for col in ["top1_share", "bottom50_share", "g10"]:
    if col in df.columns:
        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors="coerce")

# Restrict to 19102020
df = df[(df["year"] >= 1910) & (df["year"] <= 2020)]
df = df.sort_values(["country", "year"])


# Two-axis overlay plot
def overlay_plot(country, ineq_col, title, ylabel_ineq):
    temp = df[df["country"] == country]

    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

    # Left axis  inequality
    color1 = "tab:red"
    ax1.set_ylabel(ylabel_ineq, color=color1)
    ax1.plot(temp["year"], temp[ineq_col], color=color1, linewidth=2)
    ax1.tick_params(axis="y", labelcolor=color1)

    # Right axis  growth
    ax2 = ax1.twinx()
    color2 = "tab:blue"
    ax2.set_ylabel("10-Year GDP per Capita Growth (%)", color=color2)
    ax2.plot(temp["year"], temp["g10"], color=color2, linewidth=2)
    ax2.tick_params(axis="y", labelcolor=color2)

    plt.title(f"{title}\n{country}")
    fig.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Top 1% Income Share vs Growth

for c in countries:
    overlay_plot(
        country=c,
        ineq_col="top1_share",
        title="Top 1% Income Share vs Long-Run Growth (19102020)",
        ylabel_ineq="Top 1% Income Share (%)"
    )

Closing Thoughts

My goal is to better understand the impact of inequality on economic growth or lack thereof. My hypothesis is that economic growth is negatively correlated with inequality, in other words that high inequality stagnates economic growth. With this historical data in hand, I can gain insights into their relationship over at least the past century and hopefully begin to theorize on the potential policy implications presented by that relationship. From what I've shown above, it appears that there is a relationship and that my hypothesis may hold true, but more analysis and consideration is needed.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'qtpdf', 'qtpng', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
